\begin_layout Standard
The hydrodynamic state right behind the front is defined by Rankine–Hugoniot
 conditions, which express conservation of fluxes of mass, momentum and
 total specific enthalpy across the detonation front:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\backslash
label{eq:intro:cj-znd:cj:conservation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\rho_{\text{b}}\left(u_{\text{b}}-D\right) & =-\rho_{\textrm{\text{\text{b}}}}D,\\
p_{\text{b}}+\rho_{\text{b}}\left(u_{\text{b}}-D\right)^{2} & =p_{\text{a}}+\rho_{\text{a}}D^{2},\\
e_{\text{b}}+\frac{p_{\text{b}}}{\rho_{\text{b}}}+\frac{\left(u_{\text{b}}-D\right)^{2}}{2} & =e_{\textrm{b}}+\frac{p_{\textrm{b}}}{\rho_{\textrm{b}}}+\frac{D^{2}}{2},
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 denote density, velocity, pressure, and internal energy, respectively;
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the detonation velocity; subscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes quantities in ambient mixture ahead of the detonation wave; subscript
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

b
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes quantities in burned mixture behind the detonation wave.
 The ambient mixture is defined by known quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\text{a}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{a}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\text{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we have four unknowns (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

) and only three equations (
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\mathrm{b}}$
\end_inset

 is found using thermodynamic relation 
\begin_inset Formula $e=e\left(p,\rho\right)$
\end_inset

), thus, the closure condition is required.
 It appears in this theory as the hypothesis based on the following observation.
 Detonation wave is stable, thus, the burned state is isolated from the
 acoustic waves that can appear behind the wave due to the expansion of
 reaction products.
 Therefore, at the burned state local flow velocity relative to the detonation
 wave must be sonic:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{\mathrm{\text{b}}}-D=c_{\text{b}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

 is the sound speed in burned mixture.
 This condition coupled with conditions
