\begin_layout Standard
As soon as it was discovered experimentally
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "White1961,Voytsekhovskiy1963"

\end_inset

 that ZND detonation in gases was not stable, the question of the stability
 analysis arose.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Shchelkin1959"

\end_inset

 formulated criterion of stability of ZND detonation based on a simplifying
 assumption that the detonation front is followed by a region of constant
 state coupled with infinitesimally thin reaction zone (square-wave detonation
 model).
 Consequent work on the detonation stability was focused mainly on three
 branches: linear stability analysis, asymptotic analysis, and direct numerical
 simulations.
 Below we review some of the most important works of the first and third
 branches for the one- and two-dimensional detonations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Linear stability analysis.

\series default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Erpenbeck1962"

\end_inset

 formulated the problem of detonation stability as a hydrodynamic stability
 problem for three-dimensional flow with several reactions and proposed
 an approach for the solution, and applied his approach to the flow with
 one-step irreversible Arrhenius-type reaction
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Erpenbeck1964"

\end_inset

.
 Erpenbeck's technique consisted of linearization of the equations about
 steady-state solution and application of the Laplace transform in time
 to reduce the problem to a system of linear inhomogeneous ODEs and then
 analysis of the poles of the transform function in a complex plane.
 The extensive overview of the Erpenbeck's work, as well as of other early
 studies, is provided in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Fickett2000"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Later, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "LeeStewart1990"

\end_inset

 studied linear stability of one-dimensional detonation using normal-mode
 approach and posing stability problem as a two-point eigenvalue problem
 with linearized Rankine–Hugoniot conditions at the shock and with boundedness
 condition in the end of the reaction zone.
 The latter condition (also known as radiation condition) serves as a dispersion
 relation and mathematically means that eigenfunctions remain bounded or,
 from physical point of view, that no information propagates from the rear
 end of the reaction zone to the lead shock.
 To solve the boundary-value problem they used the shooting method coupled
 with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

carpet search
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to find the domain of attraction of the boundedness-condition function.
 The authors obtained neutral stability curves in different parameter spaces.
 In the space 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

heat release–overdrive factor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 they found qualitative agreement with the results of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Erpenbeck1964"

\end_inset

.
 Their main conclusion was that the increase of the degree of overdrive
 stabilizes the ZND solutions, while the increase of activation energy destabili
zes the ZND solution.
 Later, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sharpe1997"

\end_inset

 modified the approach of Lee & Stewart by deriving asymptotic value of
 flow state at the end of the reaction zone and consequently (using this
 state as an initial value) integrating towards the shock.
 As integration in the direction of the shock is better conditioned, it
 allowed to consider not only the range of the parameters of Lee & Stewart
 (where his results agrees with theirs), but also to extend the analysis
 to the larger activation energy range, where he found pure exponential
 growth of instability in contrast with the results of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Buckmaster1988"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet*
key "Short1998"

\end_inset

