\begin_layout Section
Overview of the present work
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:intro:overview"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the present work we aim to study the stability of ZND solutions—steady,
 one-dimensional solutions—of different detonation models varying from Fickett's
 detonation analog to models based on reactive Euler equations with realistic
 thermochemistry.
 The approach we use to reach our goal is based on combination of the features
 of linear stability analysis via normal modes with direct numerical simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The high-level description of our approach is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the ZND solution for the given model.
 This step includes the problem of finding the CJ detonation velocity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Linearize the system about the ZND solution.
 Linearize the Rankine–Hugoniot conditions.
 The result is a linear system in which unknowns are perturbations of the
 ZND solution.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:intro:overview:linearize"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Pose the initial boundary-value problem consisting of the linear system
 along with linearized Rankine–Hugoniot conditions as a boundary condition
 on the upstream boundary and outflow boundary condition on the downstream
 boundary.
 Set initial condition using functions of magnitude much smaller than the
 magnitude of ZND quantities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve the obtained linear initial boundary-value problem numerically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Postprocess the solution to extract the growth rates and frequencies of
 the perturbations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This approach has several advantages over pure linear stability analysis
 or direct numerical simulations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solution of linear hyperbolic problem allows to avoid any complications
 connected with presence of secondary shocks in detonation wave;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
solution of linear hyperbolic problem with smooth initial condition is smooth
 as well, therefore, low-diffusion and low-dispersion numerical method can
 be used to obtain it;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
solution of linear stability problem numerically avoids imposing of radiation
 boundary condition at the downstream boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, numerical computation of linearized problem can be used to verify
 the result of direct numerical simulation of fully nonlinear problem.
\end_layout

